 bring to life a place where the past continues to resonate for all its residents, even as the city hurtles forward into a future marked by transience and transition. By skillfully blending ethnographic and visual approaches, Hong Kong offers a fascinating guide to a city that is at once unique in its recent history and exemplary of our globalized present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBritishzChinazHong KongxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  amigration, migrant, worker, landscape, daily life, china, asia, asian, eastern world, sociology, sociologist, 1990s, power, government, colonial, colonialism, united kingdom, city, urban, empire, british, britain, postcolonial, change, fieldwork, photography, illustrated, photographs, expatriate, minority, southeast, resident, global, globalization, ethnic group.1 aHarper, Douglas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022644856540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226448589423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226448589/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles